<br>
Rangers up to 50, in fact any melee up to about 50 can tank about equally, in experience situations.  After 50 it takes progressively better gear for a Non-plate (this now includes monks) to tank the bigger mobs, but it is still very feasible for Rangers and monks to tank in experience groups all the way up to 60, at least.<br>
<br>
When Kunark came out, Rangers were given none, absolutely zero, defensive skill increases.  Couple this with old world gear, no agro reduction, and harder hitting Kunark mobs and you have the seeds for a million +1 &quot;Ranger down&quot; jokes.<br>
<br>
Since then Rangers have been given 40 more defence points post 50, better dodge, better gear, Jolt line (agro reduction similar to concussion for wizards), and the possibility to situationally do lots of damage with their previously useless bows (takes about 45 AA's, so don't call it &quot;free&quot; damage).<br>
<br>
Rangers are an excelelnt utility class.  They are to melee's, what shaman are to casters.  A jack of all trades, master of one...  That is agro control.  Rangers can take agro at will, and pass it back nearly as easily as a rogue.  If you are a caster or cleric and are agroed, you should much prefer a ranger taunting it off you, than a warrior.<br>
<br>
Anyway's, as mages I would think you would be slow to jump on bandwagon's about a classes utility, as you have suffered under similar misconceptions in the past.<br>
